pTitle: Samsung 32GB BAR (METAL) USB 3.0 Flash Drive (MUF-32BA/AM)
rText:
My 3.0 Corsair Flash Voyager drives are significantly faster. I have the 32gb and 128gb Samsung drives and copying cyclically bounces from a high of around 16mb/s down to 1gb/s. Very annoying. They both do this. The 32gb Flash Voyager maintains a nearly constant rate.

These things also get stupid hot. The metal housing is nice for a heatsink but removing one of these out of my Shield TV was actually uncomfortable it was so hot. I dont think they will last long.
rTitle: Decent price but there are much faster drives - get stupid hot to the touch

pTitle: SanDisk Cruzer 64GB USB 2.0 Flash Drive (SDCZ36-064G-B35)
rText: I wish I could give it zero stars because I don't even get to use this product. I should have looked at all of the negative reviews, I'm usually much better about researching a product properly before buying it. I am having the exact same problem as so many of the other negative reviewers. I have not been able to use this device on ANY computer as it is in "write-protection" mode and I cannot undo it. It allowed me to set-up the drive to some degree, I made it all the way to setting up the passcode. But as soon as I typed my password in twice (one was for confirmation), the disk requested my passcode to move on further and my password magically did not work. So now I can't even get into the drive even if it somehow stopped being write-protected. I am angry that I spent money on a product that DOES NOT WORK and I do not get to use. Don't waste your money.
rTitle: Defective and a Waste of My Money; Don't Buy

rText: Not what I expected when purchasing a 64GB flash drive. I know the net GB is a bit lower than what's stated, but I was limited to 57GB on the one that arrived new from amazon. There are also many other reviews that indicate there is an issue with these items becoming useless due to an internal error that seems to occur in a statistically significant pattern to warrant no purchasing this brand in the future. Upon further inspection, I see these are made by Western Digital and I can say I'm solidly not a fan. I have about 750GB of lost data between two failed hard drives made by WD. They are a few years old and I can't get the devices to turn or even register on my system. I'm out when it comes to Western Digital products
rTitle: Beware what lurks below...these are made by Western Digital.

pTitle: JOIOT 16GB USB 2.0 Flash Drive Thumb Drive Jump Drive with LED for Fold Data Storage, Memory Stick, Zip Drives, Pen Drive - Black (4-Pack)
rText: I highly pondered returning them as the write speed is painful (~2MB/s), but after some testing of my older 'cheap' drives I decided they were within a tolerable range. File size R/W scales normally and a mixed file transfer paces average, so they're a good 'value', but don't expect performance. Write speed hovers at ~17MB/s. Aside from functionality, they're physically decent, but I noticed the LEDs are inconsistent in that they don't like the same way in each. I had them range from a tiny pin of light at the end of the unit to one that looked like I lit a halogen inside the casing. IDK why these manufacturers (all of them it seems) will send you like half of the number of wrist straps (not even sure I'll use, but they're included) to that of the number of drives.

pDescr:
Color:White  |  Product Packaging:Standard Packaging
Charge Both of Your Devices Simultaneously At Record Time!
If you're always looking for a plug to charge your phone, then our BoostCube 2 charger is the perfect solution for you!
Now you can charge two electronic devices using just one plug! It's easy, fast and can maximize the charging efficiency, so your phone will be fully charged in half the time, thanks to our SmartID Technology!

Compact & Perfect for Travel
Wide range 100 - 240V AC input allows you to travel all over the world with one charger; Compact portable design and lightweight (only 2.47 OZ) perfect for travelling

Compatible With Most Electronic Devices
It's widely compatible with mobile device, including but not limited to: Phones, Tablets, External Battery Pack, GPS, PSP, PS4 Controller, Bluetooth Speaker/Headphones, Mp3 Players and USB Powered Devices.

Specifically, it's compatible with:
-Apple iPhone 7, Se, 6s, 6s Plus, 6 Plus, 5, 5C, 5S, iPad Pro/Mini/Air
-Samsung Galaxy S7, S6 Edge, S6, S5, S4, S3, Note 5 4, Tab(at 5V/2A)
-HTC One 10 A9 X V S M9 M8,LG G5, Optimus F3,Nexus 5 6 7 9 10, Motorola Droid RAZR MAXX(at 5V/1.5A)
-Blackberry, Kindle (Fire) and more! (at 5V/1A)

Please remember that it's NOT compatible with Macbook, iPod nano, iPod Classic, HP TouchPad, Dell Venue 11 Pro and Asus Tablets.

Extra Specifications And Package Contents
It has an input of AC 100~240V 50/60Hz, an output of 5V/4.8A (each 2.4A max), it's 2.08 x 2.08 x 1.12 inches big and weighs 2.59oz (82g). Inside The package you will find 1 iClever IC-TC02 Dual USB Wall Charger, 1 User Manual and 1 Warranty Card.

Warning:
Do not charge attempt to your device using an old faulty wall outlet. Doing so may cause damage to your device and cause the charger to spark.
Do not use the BoostCube to charge a device who's input power exceeds rating power 5V/2.4A

Overview:
USB 3.0 is the third major version of the Universal Serial Bus (USB) standard for interfacing computers and electronic devices. USB 3.0 connectors are usually distinguished from their USB 2.0 counterparts by blue color-coding of the receptacles and plugs, and the initials SS. Use this cable when you want the fastest transfer speeds between your computer and external device.

USB 3.0 is the third major version of the Universal Serial Bus (USB) standard for interfacing computers and electronic devices. Among other improvements, USB 3.0 adds the new transfer mode SuperSpeed (SS) that can transfer data at up to 5 Gbit/s (625 MB/s), which is about ten times faster than the USB 2.0 standard. USB 3.0 connectors are usually distinguished from their USB 2.0 counterparts by blue color-coding of the receptacles and plugs, and the initials SS. Use this cable when you want the fastest transfer speeds between your computer and external device.

pTitle: Sandisk Extreme Go 64GB USB 3.0 (3.1 Gen 1) Type-A USB Flash Drive - SDCZ800-064G-G46
rText:
I have two of the older version of the same flash disk for some time which lead me to buying this one.
The poor review is due to the way the company is handling the support calls.
I received the product and because of the confidence I had in it, tried to copy my private and confidential data on it immediately. The flash drive became write protected in middle of the data transfer and I could not fix it no matter what I tried.

I tried the manufacturers support page and found the suggested procedure for the write protection "remove the drive and plug it back, if problem persists fill out RMA form".
I filled out a comprehensive form and received an email telling me someone will contact me... and "We assume no liability for any data residing on your returned device" if I wanted a replacement.

This is very irresponsible for a company that makes flash disks to save and protect peoples' data.
I will destroy the drive and won't ask for refund because the data on it is very sensitive. Also I will never endorse their products and will never purchase one.
rTitle: Hopefully your device won't break because: "We assume no liability for any data residing on your returned device"

pTitle: Sandisk Extreme Go 64GB USB 3.0 (3.1 Gen 1) Type-A USB Flash Drive - SDCZ800-064G-G46
rText:
Needed to backup some work-related folders on my laptop. I did some research and this 'Extreme Go' was recommended without breaking the bank or having super-duper transfer speeds. Since I'm going a backup, speed is not a concern, but what IS a concern is reliability. This 'Extreme Go' got top marks no matter where I looked or what I read.
I bought two.
The laptop had no problem recognizing the 64GB space and the 'thumb protection software' (encryption) ran flawlessly. It took about 2 hours but over 57GB was 'backed up & encrypted' without any error messages or warnings. I then shutdown and dismounted the thumbdrive.
After the backup was completed, I rebooted the laptop and attached the thumb, much in the way I would if somebody messed with my laptop and I had to, from scratch and quickly, get access to or recover what had been messed with (deleted/moved). The backup software was able to de-crypt (quickly!) and list all the folders and files. Impressive!

I've used 512Mb, 8GB and even 16GB thumbs, but have never really trusted really-high capacity thumbs. So, I was really pleasantly surprised to find that this 64GB thumb not only performed flawlessly but easily and... reliably.
rTitle: I did some research and this 'Extreme Go' was recommended without breaking the bank or having super-duper transfer speeds

pTitle: Sandisk Extreme Go 64GB USB 3.0 (3.1 Gen 1) Type-A USB Flash Drive - SDCZ800-064G-G46
rText: Be warned, this unit is flimsily constructed and thus will fail if you ever accidentally knock it against anything while it is inserted in a laptop USB. When one pushes the switch forward and extends the USB connector so it can be inserted, there is not much protection left in the flimsy plastic shell to keep the unit from flexing or wobbling. If you set your laptop down on a bed, for example, and there is anything pressing on the underside of the Sandisk unit, such as part of a comforter, the entire unit will flex upward, putting stress on the soldered connections between the USB jack and the internal board that holds the flash chip. Only purchase this if you will use it in a laptop that rests on a desk and never moves from that safe surface. If you use it in any device you may drop, or set on an uneven surface, you'll risk breaking it due to its poor design.
rTitle: Easily broken due to less-than-sturdy design.

pTitle: Sandisk Extreme Go 64GB USB 3.0 (3.1 Gen 1) Type-A USB Flash Drive - SDCZ800-064G-G46
rText:
Okay let me start off by saying that if you're just going to be using this to occasionally move files around you should be fine. But if you're a crazy person like me and you like to use computer hardware in creative ways and extreme ways, steer clear of this device.

I downloaded a Windows 10 ISO with the Windows Media Creation Tool and then used Hasleo WinToUSB software to install Windows 10 onto the USB drive while the drive was plugged into a USB 3.0 port. Towards the end of setting up the system I was extracting the network driver from the motherboard manufacturer website and I noticed that the extraction would start and stop randomly, going from 40-50 MB/s down to ZERO. This probably happened 4 or 5 times before it finished fully extracting.

I feel the USB stick and notice it's super hot. Then I look closer, "Huh, that's not right. Wait a second... HOLY CRAP!" the stick had literally bent itself from the plastic element of the USB plug overheating and overheating the aluminum around it.

THIS IS LITERALLY EXTREMELY DANGEROUS! EXTREME HEAT WILL DAMAGE THIS DEVICE WHEN USED AS BOOTABLE OS IN USB 3.0 or 3.1 PORT OR DURING FILE EXTRACTION FROM COMPRESSED FILES LIKE ZIP AND RAR!

I noticed after plugging it into the USB 2.0 port that it still works just fine as a bootable OS and doesn't get anywhere near as hot as when it's plugged into a USB 3.0 port.

The design of this device as far as heat dissipation goes is garbage and downright dangerous if you plan to use it for extended periods of time or for any sort of extraction or encryption of files, at least when it's plugged into a USB 3.0 or 3.1 port.
rTitle: !!!**EXTREME HEAT WILL DAMAGE THIS DEVICE WHEN USED AS BOOTABLE OS IN USB 3.0 or 3.1 PORT**!!!

pTitle: JOIOT 32GB USB 3.0 Flash Drive Thumb Drive Jump Drive with LED for Fold Data Storage, Memory Stick, Zip Drives, Pen Drive - Black / Red (2-Pack)
rText:
Excellent value for the money for this size memory. I have purchased several of these and never had an issue with any of them. They simply work as they are supposed to right out of the package. And thank you to Joiot for not preloading introductory software on these like some other manufacturers do. The come completely blank and ready to use (but be sure to re-format first; see next paragraph).

Now, a very minor gripe. These come preformatted in FAT32. The FAT32 file structure was obsolete years ago and I don't understand why these external drive manufacturers continue to use it. It's a very simple, quick process to reformat these in NTFS - less than half a minute. So you should do this before using it for the first time.

rText:

good sound quality, I didn't hear any hiss created by this device. Only a little bit of his from my microphone.

Customer service was great too. Before purchasing this I asked a question about if this device would work with my microphone and the seller promptly responded with a detailed answer.

How to use this device:
To use this as mic/headphone port on a mac, go to "System Preferences", click on the "Sound" icon, and switch your "Input" and "Output" to "USB Device." (As shown in screen shots)
To use for garage band, go to "Preferences", and click on the "Audio" tab. Switch your input and output to "USB Device." (As shown in screen shots)
For any other program, the set up should be very similar.

pTitle: AmazonBasics USB 2.0 Cable - A-Male to Mini-B - 6 Feet (1.8 Meters)
rText:
It's great to see this type of USB cable is still available because some devices still use it.
I got it for an Aukey lamp because they sent me a micro cable with it and wouldn't send me a proper A male to Mini B.
If you own a Play Station 3 you can also use this type of cable with it.
It's six feet which offers great flexibility.
